article.headline: Catchings, Williams lead Fever pace
article.linkText: Indiana crushes Washington to end six-game slide
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP)-- Tamika Catchings gave her second Olympian
performance within a week.

Catchings returned from the Athens Olympics and notched 16
points, seven assists and six rebounds to help the Indiana Fever
snap a six-game losing streak with a 75-58 win over the Washington
Mystics on Wednesday.

Natalie Williams added 16 points and 12 rebounds for the Fever.

Catchings started for the U.S. team in Saturday's gold-medal
game, a 74-63 win over Australia. The 6-foot-1 forward looked
fatigued but kept working both ends of the court over 34 minutes.

"The [jet lag] was there, I could feel it," Catchings said,
with a laugh. "But I want to help this team. I'm excited about
being back."

Kelly Schumacher added 16 points on 8-of-12 shooting and Kelly
Miller scored 13 for the Fever, who went from first to worst in the
Eastern Conference before the monthlong Olympic break.

With the win, Indiana (13-15) is a half-game ahead of last-place
Washington (12-15).

Indiana coach Brian Winters liked his team's intensity heading
into the final six games of the season.

"We really needed to play with a sense of urgency," Winters
said. "We needed to get a win and get off on the right foot.
Anybody can be a playoff team...and win the East."

Chasity Melvin led Washington with a game-high 19 points. Alana
Beard had 12 points and Murriel Page added nine.

The Mystics played without scoring-leader Chamique Holdsclaw,
who was placed on the injured list Tuesday. She will miss two more
games with an undisclosed health problem.

"We're just trying to find the right combinations," Washington
coach Michael Adams said.

The Fever led 34-28 at halftime, but Washington cut it to 40-38
with just under 17 minutes left. Indiana went on a 12-4 run and
secured the win. The Fever shot 53 percent from the field and
dominated the boards, 37-25.
